<span id="freeTextContainer17498791599809218028">I really enjoy reading great southern writers, a group that includes Erskine Caldwell. <i>Tobacco Road</i> is a wonderful, if depressing, journey into backcountry, rural America. Themes of poverty, untreated physical and mental conditions, death, education, racism, incest, ‘bad luck,’ a tolerance, maybe even a wish, for disrepair, irony, and predatory commercial practices suffered by poor farmers all run through this work. I wonder, how much of this world yet remains in this country since a desire to m</span>
  <span id="freeText17498791599809218028" style="display:none">I really enjoy reading great southern writers, a group that includes Erskine Caldwell. <i>Tobacco Road</i> is a wonderful, if depressing, journey into backcountry, rural America. Themes of poverty, untreated physical and mental conditions, death, education, racism, incest, ‘bad luck,’ a tolerance, maybe even a wish, for disrepair, irony, and predatory commercial practices suffered by poor farmers all run through this work. I wonder, how much of this world yet remains in this country since a desire to make America great again appears so fashionable?</span>
  <a data-text-id="17498791599809218028" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

