<div id="review_1281098663" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1281098663" />
    <a title="Camie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7399266-camie"><img alt="Camie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1571025937p2/7399266.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1281098663?book_show_action=true">May 15, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Camie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Camie" href="/user/show/7399266-camie">Camie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1281098663" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8806693954414173721">This is the story of the Lester&apos;s a &apos;white trash&apos; family who live on Tobacco Road in Augusta, Georgia during the Great Depression . It focuses on Jeeter the father, who appears amazingly indifferent towards his family ( including the 15 of 17 children who have already fled the poverty and devastation of the place ) Was he always like this or has the need to survive made him this way ? At times Jeeter is forced to stoop pretty low to try and sustain what&apos;s left of the family ( marrying off his 12</span>
  <span id="freeText8806693954414173721" style="display:none">This is the story of the Lester's a 'white trash' family who live on Tobacco Road in Augusta, Georgia during the Great Depression . It focuses on Jeeter the father, who appears amazingly indifferent towards his family ( including the 15 of 17 children who have already fled the poverty and devastation of the place ) Was he always like this or has the need to survive made him this way ? At times Jeeter is forced to stoop pretty low to try and sustain what's left of the family ( marrying off his 12 year old daughter) etc. but he's not a completely unlikeable guy. <br />I liked the second 1/2 of the book better as I started to understand that the frequent repetition of some sentences served to show us the helplessness of the situation. Everyday Jeeter wake’s up with a goal to change the situation, and everyday it goes undone. Mostly he thinks about plowing a field, and planting some cottonseed. We hear about this a lot, a real lot , because if only he could bring in a crop everything might be okay. Of course it never happens, but is it the lack of inertia( laziness), the loss of hope, or just plain not having the means ( or all three) that keep them stuck in this terrible existence . When someone finally manages rustle up some money these starving people buy a new car. Of course they have their reasons, but the car becomes a metaphor for their lives , as within a short time they have completely destroyed it, while saying with each new dent or ding , that it is still okay because it’s still running ( mostly) but finally ending up right back where they started. Still Jeeter pins his hopes on that yet to be planted field, and I finished this book wondering if the whole theme is hopelessness or hope ??? <br />3.5 stars. This is a book I wish I could have read as a homework group. It's one of those short seemingly simple books, but you know there's much more there. I did read it for an online club , I'll be watching for other's reviews.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8806693954414173721" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


